  <ul class="faq-list">
    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>What is the normal vitamin D level in India?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Most GPs in India use outdated 'sufficient' cutoffs of >20 ng/mL (>50 nmol/L), which is dangerously low. Optimal vitamin D levels are 40-60 ng/mL (100-150 nmol/L). Deficiency is typically defined as <20 ng/mL, insufficiency as 20-29 ng/mL. Many urban Indians hover around 15-18 ng/mL, which is borderline-severe deficiency without obvious skeletal symptoms yet.</div>
      </details>
    </li>

    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>Why are 70-80% of Indians vitamin D deficient despite sun exposure?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Multiple converging factors: (1) <em>Indoor lifestyles</em> — urban professionals spend 8-10 hours indoors, (2) <em>Pollution blocking UVB</em> — Delhi, Mumbai, Bangalore have high particulate matter that attenuates UVB, (3) <em>Dark skin requiring 3-5x more sun exposure</em> — melanin reduces UVB penetration, (4) <em>Sunscreen use</em> — necessary for skin cancer prevention but blocks UVB, (5) <em>Clothing coverage</em> — traditional and modern styles limit skin exposure. Even with 300+ sunny days, actual UVB exposure is insufficient for most Indians.</div>
      </details>
    </li>

    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>What are the symptoms of vitamin D deficiency?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans"><strong>Early symptoms:</strong> Fatigue (most common), muscle weakness, bone pain (subtle), depression and mood changes, hair loss (telogen effluvium), frequent infections and slow wound healing. Many patients dismiss these as stress or aging. <strong>Severe deficiency</strong> (prolonged <10 ng/mL) can cause rickets in children or osteomalacia (bone softening) in adults, manifesting as severe pain and fracture risk. Most deficiency in India is subclinical — you feel unwell without obvious skeletal disease.</div>
      </details>
    </li>

    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>Should I get tested for vitamin D even if I feel fine?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Yes. Vitamin D deficiency is often asymptomatic until severe. Subclinical deficiency impairs immune function, cardiovascular health, bone quality, and mood regulation. Every urban Indian should have baseline 25-hydroxy vitamin D testing. If you live in a polluted city, work indoors, have dark skin, or are above 40, testing is essential. arq. recommends testing 25-hydroxy vitamin D alongside calcium, PTH, and magnesium to get a complete picture.</div>
      </details>
    </li>

    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>Is vitamin D3 better than D2?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">Yes. <em>D3 (cholecalciferol)</em> is superior to <em>D2 (ergocalciferol)</em> for raising blood levels. D2 is cheaper and often prescribed in India, but studies show D3 is more bioavailable and produces more stable 25-hydroxy vitamin D levels. If supplementing, choose D3. Take it with dietary fat (olive oil, eggs, avocado) for optimal absorption. Many Indians take D on an empty stomach or with water, which reduces absorption significantly.</div>
