      <details>
        <summary>What is the role of K2 in vitamin D supplementation?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">K2 (menaquinone) directs calcium to bones and teeth, not soft tissues or arteries. When you take vitamin D, it increases intestinal calcium absorption. Without adequate K2, calcium may deposit in arteries (arterial calcification) instead of bones. arq. recommends taking vitamin D with K2 — either from diet (fermented foods, grass-fed dairy) or supplementation. This is especially important for women over 40 and anyone with cardiovascular risk factors.</div>
      </details>
    </li>

    <li class="faq-item">
      <details>
        <summary>How long does it take to correct vitamin D deficiency?</summary>
        <div class="faq-ans">With adequate supplementation (60,000 IU weekly for 8 weeks if severely deficient), blood levels normalize in 8-12 weeks. However, tissue saturation and symptom improvement takes longer — 3-6 months for fatigue and mood improvement, 6-12 months for bone and muscle strength recovery. Ongoing maintenance (1,000-5,000 IU daily depending on sun exposure and skin tone) prevents relapse. Compliance is key — many Indians stop after 4-6 weeks once symptoms improve, then relapse into deficiency.</div>
